#include <cstdint>

template<size_t block_size = 1024, size_t allocator_count = 100>
using tls_allocator_type = hexi::tls_block_allocator<hexi::detail::intrusive_storage<block_size>, allocator_count>;

template<size_t block_size = 1024, size_t allocator_count = 100>
void enter_thread_with_allocator(tls_allocator_type<block_size, allocator_count>& allocator) {
    // Initialize thread-local storage for the allocator
    // This typically involves creating thread-specific data structures
    allocator.attach_thread();
}

template<size_t block_size = 1024, size_t allocator_count = 100>
void exit_thread_with_allocator(tls_allocator_type<block_size, allocator_count>& allocator) {
    // Clean up thread-local storage for the allocator
    // This releases any thread-specific resources and memory blocks
    allocator.detach_thread();
}
```

The key points of this implementation:

1. **`enter_thread_with_allocator`**: Calls `attach_thread()` on the allocator to initialize thread-local storage. This sets up the necessary data structures for the current thread to use the TLS allocator.

2. **`exit_thread_with_allocator`**: Calls `detach_thread()` on the allocator to clean up thread-specific resources. This ensures that any memory blocks allocated by this thread are properly released.

The template parameters allow flexibility in configuring:
- `block_size`: Size of individual memory blocks (default 1024 bytes)
- `allocator_count`: Number of allocator instances to manage (default 100)

This pattern ensures proper thread lifecycle management for the TLS allocator, preventing memory leaks and ensuring thread-safe memory allocation.

